05196nam a22009255i 9780228012962DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280129627 a10.1515/97802280129622doi  a(DE-B1597)655043  a(OCoLC)1289995711  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKZ4082b.J37 2022 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a341.4/8qOCoLC223/eng/202206271 aJarvis, Samuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Limits of Common Humanity :bMotivating the Responsibility to Protect in a Changing Global Order /cSamuel Jarvis. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Missing Role of Humanity -- tThe Development and Contestation of the Responsibility to Protect -- tWhat Is Humanity? -- tThreats to Our Common Humanity: Why Humanity Matters -- tHumanity and the United Nations -- tAssessing the R2P's Motivational Capacity: The Role of Humanity -- tThe R2P's Key Added Value: Rethinking Implementation and Reform -- tMotivation beyond Humanity in a Changing Global Order -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat motivates states to protect populations threatened by mass atrocities beyond their own borders? Most often, states and their representatives appeal to the principle of common humanity, acknowledging a conscience-shocking quality that demands a moral response. But though the idea of a common humanity is powerful, the question remains: to what extent is it effective in motivating action?The Limits of Common Humanity provides an ambitious interdisciplinary response to this question, theorizing the role of humanity as a motivational concept by building on insights from international relations, political philosophy, and international law. Through this analysis, Samuel Jarvis examines the influence the concept of humanity has had on the creation and mission of the Responsibility to Protect (R2P) commitment, while highlighting the challenges that have restricted its application in practice. By providing a new framework for thinking about how political, legal, and moral arguments interact during the process of collective decision-making, Jarvis explores the contradictory ways in which states approach the protection of human beings from mass atrocity crimes, both domestically and internationally.In the context of a rapidly changing global order, The Limits of Common Humanity is a timely reappraisal of the R2P concept and its future application, arguing for a more politically motivated response to human protection that moves beyond an appeal for morality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanity. 0aResponsibility to protect (International law). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aBan Ki-moon.  aBurma.  aEthics.  aGeneral Assembly.  aIntervention.  aKofi Annan.  aKosovo.  aLibya.  aMyanmar.  aRwanda.  aSecurity Council.  aSovereignty.  aSri Lanka.  aSyria.  aUnited Nations.  aaccountability.  acrimes against humanity.  adecision making.  aethnic cleansing.  aforeign policy.  agenocide.  ahuman security.  ahumanitarianism.  ainternational.  amass atrocities.  apeace.  apolitical will.  aprevention.  areform.  aregional organisations.  arising powers.  aveto.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9